WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.220 --> 00:00:04.900
Okay. So I'm really excited to get this session started, and thank you

2
00:00:04.940 --> 00:00:08.740
guys for making the first session of what I hope to be

3
00:00:08.840 --> 00:00:12.720
is an amazing annual meeting. I wanted to also shout out and thank

4
00:00:12.820 --> 00:00:16.720
the Education Committee and Eddie Kukeman, who is in charge of the program,

5
00:00:17.260 --> 00:00:20.980
for really letting us delve into highlighting comorbidities

6
00:00:20.990 --> 00:00:24.619
and how they may be impacting our patients, and what the causes are.

7
00:00:24.680 --> 00:00:28.340
So I'd like to get started really by talking about what my lab's doing,

8
00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:32.259
but as a bit of background to really set the stage for the session, I

9
00:00:32.280 --> 00:00:34.480
really wanted to, assuming my slides move,

10
00:00:35.860 --> 00:00:39.220
really ask the question in the context of chemotherapy as well as other

11
00:00:39.240 --> 00:00:42.160
comorbidities. We're going to hear about radiation in a little bit.

12
00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:46.800
What is it we all think about when we think about patients that are exposed to

13
00:00:46.840 --> 00:00:50.400
chemotherapy? And I think this is probably what most people think about.

14
00:00:50.940 --> 00:00:54.520
Possibly because it's visceral, it's in your face. We see it.

15
00:00:54.580 --> 00:00:58.390
It's on TV. Unfortunately, for our patients, it's but the tip of the

16
00:00:58.460 --> 00:01:02.340
iceberg. Unfortunately, when we look at patients that are being treated

17
00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:05.980
by a variety of modalities, this certainly isn't limited to chemotherapy.

18
00:01:06.680 --> 00:01:09.950
It's going to be affected by the age of the patients for sure, the chemos they're

19
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:11.760
on, the doses they're on, the durations.

20
00:01:12.760 --> 00:01:16.160
Any one of these panoplies of effects can hit them, and the degree to it, of

21
00:01:16.240 --> 00:01:19.380
course, is affected by all of those different aspects I've already mentioned.

22
00:01:20.040 --> 00:01:23.780
And so the question is: how do we continue to increase

23
00:01:24.040 --> 00:01:27.040
lifespan for these patients, but also try to buy quality of life?

24
00:01:27.070 --> 00:01:30.540
And I think that's what this session is really about, is to think about what are

25
00:01:30.580 --> 00:01:34.520
the mechanisms driving any one of these, as well as others that aren't even

26
00:01:34.560 --> 00:01:38.000
mentioned here. And what is it we might all be able to do about it as we try to

27
00:01:38.020 --> 00:01:39.700
understand the mechanisms behind it.

28
00:01:40.760 --> 00:01:44.100
So what I wanted to do in my talk is focus on neuropathy.

29
00:01:44.260 --> 00:01:44.720
This is

30
00:01:45.540 --> 00:01:49.080
something that affects a very large percent of patients that are treated with

31
00:01:49.140 --> 00:01:52.800
chemotherapy, depending on, again, the dose, the age, the

32
00:01:52.880 --> 00:01:56.860
chemo itself. This can affect upwards of 70% of patients, and this

33
00:01:56.920 --> 00:02:00.890
is this classic stinging pains in the peripheral, in

34
00:02:00.900 --> 00:02:02.820
the fingertips and the toes or numbness.

35
00:02:03.520 --> 00:02:07.080
And unfortunately for patients, even if they beat their cancer, a large

36
00:02:07.120 --> 00:02:11.021
proportion of these patients, upwards of 30% of them, can go on

37
00:02:11.060 --> 00:02:13.300
for lifetimes to experience neuropathy.

38
00:02:13.960 --> 00:02:17.640
So this really affects quality of life, and actually, there are cases where

39
00:02:17.680 --> 00:02:21.640
patients will dose deescalate, which affects overall survival due to

40
00:02:21.650 --> 00:02:24.950
the extent to which these different symptoms are going to affect them,

41
00:02:25.660 --> 00:02:29.520
neuropathy being but one of them. And so we wanted to start thinking

42
00:02:29.560 --> 00:02:32.780
about this in the context of what the lab works in.

43
00:02:32.810 --> 00:02:36.780
And we really started to look at this in the context of what is

44
00:02:36.820 --> 00:02:40.310
it that's driving senescence, and-- excuse me, driving

45
00:02:40.460 --> 00:02:44.240
neuropathy. And one of the things that my lab has been focused on for quite

46
00:02:44.300 --> 00:02:47.760
some time is the role that senescent cells play in

47
00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:51.720
affecting neighboring cells. And chemotherapy, I have to

48
00:02:51.740 --> 00:02:54.440
tell you, is probably the best way to induce senescence.

49
00:02:54.480 --> 00:02:57.730
It's probably the first thing I give anyone who joins my lab because it always

50
00:02:57.760 --> 00:03:01.000
works, and then all the failures that come later, they can deal with, right?

51
00:03:01.040 --> 00:03:02.960
Throw chemo on cells, they senesce.

52
00:03:03.540 --> 00:03:07.120
They'll take on a variety of different changes, morphological changes.

53
00:03:07.160 --> 00:03:10.360
We call it a flattened egg morphology if we're talking in vitro.

54
00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:14.200
They can become positive for senescence-associated beta-galactosidase, which is

55
00:03:14.240 --> 00:03:18.120
this blue stain. But I think more pertinent to the talk today is they

56
00:03:18.200 --> 00:03:21.860
also express a large cadre of factors that can

57
00:03:21.900 --> 00:03:24.280
affect many different aspects of biology.

58
00:03:24.820 --> 00:03:28.650
Large numbers of inflammatory cytokines can modulate the immune response,

59
00:03:28.740 --> 00:03:32.660
both locally and systemically, ECM remodeling proteins

60
00:03:32.720 --> 00:03:35.740
that can change the structure of any tissue, again, at least

61
00:03:35.800 --> 00:03:39.690
locally, as well as growth factors that can affect both wound healing

62
00:03:39.760 --> 00:03:41.820
as well as the growth of tumor cells.

63
00:03:42.230 --> 00:03:45.960
And what was interesting to us when we were thinking about this is some of these

64
00:03:46.060 --> 00:03:49.840
SAS factors or senescence-associated secretory phenotype factors

65
00:03:49.960 --> 00:03:53.680
have been implicated in neuropathy in a variety of

66
00:03:53.720 --> 00:03:57.280
different models. And so the question we wanted to ask is: is it

67
00:03:57.400 --> 00:04:01.220
possible that senescence contributes in any demonstrable way to

68
00:04:01.440 --> 00:04:05.320
neuropathy? And if so, could we understand what the cells

69
00:04:05.380 --> 00:04:07.710
were and the mechanism by which they were driving this?

70
00:04:08.090 --> 00:04:11.570
And so we first had to set up the models, and I just wanted to take a second to

71
00:04:11.600 --> 00:04:15.480
tell you how we look at this. So if we think about the mouse paw, we

72
00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:19.500
use the mouse as a model. The little bumps on the bottom of its paw are

73
00:04:19.560 --> 00:04:23.540
similar, if you will, for neuronal innervation to our fingertips, if

74
00:04:23.600 --> 00:04:27.540
you will. And so what we see is sensory neurons will innervate

75
00:04:27.640 --> 00:04:31.040
into the dermis of those animals in the epidermis.

76
00:04:31.050 --> 00:04:32.950
And of course, this is how they're actually going to feel.

77
00:04:33.360 --> 00:04:35.900
One can measure this by staining with a neuronal marker,

78
00:04:36.800 --> 00:04:40.580
PGP 9.5. And then one just measures how far, as I just said,

79
00:04:40.640 --> 00:04:43.460
these innervate into the epidermis.

80
00:04:43.980 --> 00:04:47.160
This basically looks something like this when we measure it.

81
00:04:47.220 --> 00:04:51.120
If we put an animal, in this case, on paclitaxel or PTX for most of this talk.

82
00:04:51.560 --> 00:04:55.320
Basically, we can see this innervation in a normal mouse, and when we quantify it,

83
00:04:55.700 --> 00:04:58.300
we see a classic denervation when these animals are on.

84
00:04:58.360 --> 00:05:02.040
This is exactly what also happens to patients who go on to develop

85
00:05:02.120 --> 00:05:05.400
CIPN. And then this actually has a,

86
00:05:06.100 --> 00:05:09.560
beyond the morphologic changes I'm showing you here, can have a behavioral change

87
00:05:09.600 --> 00:05:13.220
in the mice. And we like to use a-- well, one can use a variety of different

88
00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:17.140
assays. We like to use what we lovingly refer to as the poky test or the

89
00:05:17.180 --> 00:05:20.740
Von Frey. And what one does in this particular setting is you put a filament, and

90
00:05:20.780 --> 00:05:24.720
you just push and find out how much pressure do you need to apply to the bottom of

91
00:05:24.760 --> 00:05:28.540
the planar surface of the mouse's paw to actually elicit a response,

92
00:05:28.640 --> 00:05:30.700
i.e., when do they start feeling that push.

93
00:05:31.260 --> 00:05:34.780
And basically, that denervation that I showed you in the slide

94
00:05:34.820 --> 00:05:38.700
before translates here then, in this case, to it takes more

95
00:05:38.720 --> 00:05:42.680
pressure to push. These mice are experiencing neurologic symptom, in this case, a

96
00:05:42.740 --> 00:05:46.460
numbness. It basically needs more pressure for them to actually feel what's

97
00:05:46.560 --> 00:05:50.460
actually happening. And so we wanted to really ask the question

98
00:05:50.520 --> 00:05:54.460
then, given the fact that many of the SAS factors that we have looked

99
00:05:54.500 --> 00:05:58.480
at in other aspects of biology have been implicated in CIPN,

100
00:05:58.560 --> 00:06:01.980
was it possible that senescence was contributing to this phenotype in some

101
00:06:02.080 --> 00:06:05.668
way?And so when we start thinking about the nervous system and

102
00:06:05.848 --> 00:06:09.217
neurons themselves, there are many different places we may need to pay attention.

103
00:06:09.688 --> 00:06:13.648
In the dorsal root ganglia, this is where the cell bodies find themselves, then

104
00:06:13.688 --> 00:06:17.288
they obviously run along the nerve, and then to the eventual

105
00:06:17.388 --> 00:06:19.278
axons that innervate into the periphery.

106
00:06:19.948 --> 00:06:22.488
In the interest of time, I'm not going to show you all the negative data.

107
00:06:22.538 --> 00:06:26.088
I'm just going to summarize by saying despite our best efforts, we were unable to

108
00:06:26.108 --> 00:06:29.658
find any evidence of senescence in the dorsal root ganglia, and

109
00:06:29.748 --> 00:06:33.628
furthermore, along the entire sural and sciatic nerve, there was no evidence of

110
00:06:33.668 --> 00:06:37.068
senescent cells. And so we wanted to go on and focus then on the

111
00:06:37.108 --> 00:06:41.028
periphery. And when we started to first just look, we found that there

112
00:06:41.068 --> 00:06:44.408
was a significant increase in p16 mRNA expression

113
00:06:45.128 --> 00:06:48.708
in animals that were treated with paclitaxel, and this was also true at the

114
00:06:48.748 --> 00:06:52.188
protein level. So why focus on p16?

115
00:06:52.628 --> 00:06:55.908
Well, p16 by itself is not a senescent marker.

116
00:06:56.128 --> 00:06:59.868
It is a marker that often tells us we may have senescent cells.

117
00:07:00.228 --> 00:07:03.948
In addition to that, we have a number of tools in which we can use to manipulate

118
00:07:04.288 --> 00:07:07.247
p16-positive cells, senescent cells in this case.

119
00:07:07.568 --> 00:07:11.428
And so we wanted to ask the question then, given this increase in p16

120
00:07:11.508 --> 00:07:15.208
in the periphery specifically, are these cells contributing to the

121
00:07:15.248 --> 00:07:18.868
CIPN or the neuropathy that these animals were experiencing?

122
00:07:19.508 --> 00:07:22.868
And as I just said, we have a number of tools that allow us to do this.

123
00:07:23.228 --> 00:07:26.168
And one of our favorite tools that we start with when we're thinking about a

124
00:07:26.188 --> 00:07:30.148
potential role for senescence is a mouse model that Darren Baker created many

125
00:07:30.208 --> 00:07:32.408
years ago when he was in Jan Van Deursen's lab.

126
00:07:33.028 --> 00:07:36.708
And just briefly, the way this particular model works is there's a minimal

127
00:07:36.748 --> 00:07:40.508
p16 promoter, hence our fixation with p16, that can

128
00:07:40.568 --> 00:07:44.348
drive an inducible suicide gene. And so what this allows

129
00:07:44.408 --> 00:07:47.938
us to do is basically kill senescent cells in a relatively

130
00:07:48.088 --> 00:07:52.028
specific manner. And so we used this animal and first

131
00:07:52.068 --> 00:07:55.748
went back and looked again in those planar surfaces in the periphery for a

132
00:07:55.788 --> 00:07:59.248
marker of senescence beyond p16, in this case, senescence-associated

133
00:07:59.308 --> 00:08:03.248
beta-galactosidase. And I hope what you can appreciate is we see significant

134
00:08:03.328 --> 00:08:07.188
increases in the periphery of animals treated with paclitaxel.

135
00:08:07.528 --> 00:08:11.268
And when we use that and activate the inducible suicide gene by applying

136
00:08:11.308 --> 00:08:15.008
AP, which is the drug that dimerizes the suicide gene, we

137
00:08:15.048 --> 00:08:17.028
significantly eliminate, again, those

138
00:08:17.848 --> 00:08:20.488
SA-beta-gal positive cells in the periphery.

139
00:08:21.228 --> 00:08:25.108
And so we had two different markers to argue that senescence was there and that

140
00:08:25.148 --> 00:08:28.588
this mouse model might actually be affecting the presence of these cells.

141
00:08:29.088 --> 00:08:32.788
In addition, perhaps not surprising then, if we also go back in now and look in the

142
00:08:32.828 --> 00:08:35.968
periphery of animals in which we've induced the suicide gene for the

143
00:08:36.009 --> 00:08:39.068
p16 protein, as I showed you with the

144
00:08:39.228 --> 00:08:42.968
SA-beta-gal, the increase in the p16 positive there with the blue

145
00:08:43.048 --> 00:08:46.568
bar is significantly reduced when we activate the suicide gene.

146
00:08:46.628 --> 00:08:50.128
So we can certainly modulate the presence and absence of these cells within the

147
00:08:50.168 --> 00:08:53.477
periphery. And so what happens then to the symptoms of

148
00:08:53.488 --> 00:08:57.398
neuropathy? When we first look at innervation into these animals,

149
00:08:57.428 --> 00:09:00.968
again, I hope what you can appreciate is upon paclitaxel, we see significant

150
00:09:00.988 --> 00:09:04.608
denervation in these animals, which is completely obliterated when we kill

151
00:09:04.708 --> 00:09:06.248
senescent cells in the periphery.

152
00:09:06.708 --> 00:09:10.448
And importantly, this translates to a behavioral effect.

153
00:09:10.757 --> 00:09:14.568
That numbness that these animals were experiencing there with the PTX in the blue

154
00:09:14.648 --> 00:09:18.188
bar is completely abrogated, again, when we eliminate

155
00:09:18.248 --> 00:09:20.708
senescent cells from the periphery of these animals.

156
00:09:22.008 --> 00:09:25.808
So we can prevent it. Of course, one of the questions is,

157
00:09:26.148 --> 00:09:29.338
is the presence of senescent cells also maintaining this phenotype?

158
00:09:29.428 --> 00:09:31.288
Can we actually rescue the phenotype?

159
00:09:31.688 --> 00:09:35.428
And so to do that, what we decided to do was, again, the same experiment we had

160
00:09:35.468 --> 00:09:39.068
done in the past, but this time, instead of eliminating senescence

161
00:09:39.108 --> 00:09:42.928
throughout the course of the paclitaxel treatment, instead what we did

162
00:09:43.228 --> 00:09:47.128
was to let these animals develop symptoms of CIPN

163
00:09:47.268 --> 00:09:50.808
and then go in, eliminate the senescent cells, and ask what actually

164
00:09:50.848 --> 00:09:53.548
happens. Here again, I'm showing innervation.

165
00:09:53.648 --> 00:09:57.368
As expected, if we wait 10 days in this case, these animals

166
00:09:57.488 --> 00:10:00.608
have evidence of axonal denervation.

167
00:10:01.108 --> 00:10:04.978
And when we kill senescent cells after that, we actually get a reinnervation

168
00:10:05.088 --> 00:10:06.708
of the epidermis within these animals.

169
00:10:07.068 --> 00:10:10.998
And importantly for the animals, again, I think at the end of the day,

170
00:10:11.068 --> 00:10:14.798
it really is, what is the behavioral effect on these

171
00:10:14.848 --> 00:10:18.658
animals? And so here what I'm showing you is, we have three lines here

172
00:10:18.748 --> 00:10:22.468
now. So again, in the blue there with paclitaxel, these animals have developed

173
00:10:22.507 --> 00:10:26.118
numbness. And then if we don't treat them, we just leave them for another

174
00:10:26.248 --> 00:10:30.128
month, what you'll notice is their paw threshold there actually drops below

175
00:10:30.168 --> 00:10:33.188
the controls. This is actually an indication of pain.

176
00:10:33.288 --> 00:10:36.988
So if we leave these animals untreated for over a month, they move

177
00:10:37.068 --> 00:10:40.708
from numbness to pain, which can also happen with patients.

178
00:10:41.128 --> 00:10:45.048
Importantly, if at the time they've developed numbness, we now start

179
00:10:45.088 --> 00:10:48.288
to eliminate the senescent cells, this pain is

180
00:10:48.328 --> 00:10:51.628
completely reversed, and these animals go back to baseline.

181
00:10:51.688 --> 00:10:54.148
So they've reinnervated into the periphery, but they've also

182
00:10:57.208 --> 00:10:59.348
eliminated the behavioral effect that's ahead of them.

183
00:11:00.088 --> 00:11:01.828
So that's a genetic approach. Can we

184
00:11:02.628 --> 00:11:04.488
confirm this with a pharmacologic approach?

185
00:11:04.528 --> 00:11:08.068
And so to do this, we like to use a drug class called senolytics.

186
00:11:08.488 --> 00:11:11.088
This is a class of drugs that can kill senescent cells.

187
00:11:11.668 --> 00:11:15.648
How, in fact, these drugs particularly work is still an area of debate within the

188
00:11:15.708 --> 00:11:18.928
field. But using a number of controls, usually

189
00:11:19.888 --> 00:11:23.808
p16-positive, SA-beta-gal cells really are the only cells that we see

190
00:11:23.828 --> 00:11:27.668
that are demonstrably eliminated when we use, in this case, dasatinib

191
00:11:27.708 --> 00:11:30.068
and quercetin as a mixed combination.

192
00:11:30.668 --> 00:11:34.248
I'm showing you the data in a little bit different way here, but basically, again,

193
00:11:34.328 --> 00:11:38.008
this was where we let the animals, after treatment, develop

194
00:11:38.088 --> 00:11:41.818
pain. So what you can see with that paw threshold in the blue and the red, these

195
00:11:41.848 --> 00:11:43.598
are animals treated with paclitaxel.

196
00:11:44.068 --> 00:11:47.268
Their paw thresholds have dropped lower than their baselines.

197
00:11:47.308 --> 00:11:49.988
In other words, they've gone on to develop pain.

198
00:11:50.088 --> 00:11:53.648
Once they've developed the pain, if we now start to treat them with our

199
00:11:53.688 --> 00:11:54.968
senolytics, this is the red

200
00:11:56.028 --> 00:11:59.718
line if you look at it, we actually recover these animals back to wild type,

201
00:12:00.148 --> 00:12:03.888
arguing that, again, both with a pharmacologic approach as well as the genetic

202
00:12:03.928 --> 00:12:07.848
approach, by eliminating senescent cells in the periphery, we can actually

203
00:12:07.928 --> 00:12:11.768
reverse the symptoms of CIPN.So I told you

204
00:12:11.808 --> 00:12:15.708
that the only evidence of increases in p16 that we could find were in

205
00:12:15.768 --> 00:12:19.708
fact in the periphery. And so the question is, what were the cells that are

206
00:12:19.808 --> 00:12:22.288
driving this and how are they driving this?

207
00:12:22.968 --> 00:12:26.308
What do you do when you have no idea? Hope single cell will lead the way.

208
00:12:26.488 --> 00:12:30.387
And so we decided to run some single cell on the planar surfaces of those

209
00:12:30.468 --> 00:12:34.448
animals. And while it's a small subset of fibroblasts, the

210
00:12:34.648 --> 00:12:38.498
only p16 that we could identify within that single cell data set was

211
00:12:38.528 --> 00:12:42.388
in fact a small subset of fibroblasts by at least GSO

212
00:12:42.428 --> 00:12:45.668
scores, they show an increase in overall senescent signature.

213
00:12:46.508 --> 00:12:47.608
So we went in,

214
00:12:48.408 --> 00:12:51.288
I have a thing in my lab, I don't believe RNA without protein.

215
00:12:51.368 --> 00:12:55.097
So if we went in and then stained the planar surfaces of these animals

216
00:12:55.568 --> 00:12:59.528
for PDGF-R alpha, which is a marker of fibroblasts, not by itself

217
00:12:59.688 --> 00:13:03.648
the only marker, and p16, I hope what you can appreciate with the

218
00:13:03.668 --> 00:13:07.568
connotation there over to the right, is that we see an increase in p16

219
00:13:07.628 --> 00:13:11.508
positive, that should be on the label, I apologize, a PDGF-R positive

220
00:13:11.668 --> 00:13:15.388
cells, and those are eliminated when we treat the animals with AP.

221
00:13:15.508 --> 00:13:19.288
Again, this is our way to genetically eliminate p16 positive

222
00:13:19.368 --> 00:13:20.288
senescent cells.

223
00:13:21.148 --> 00:13:24.988
This isn't just in mice. If we take samples, and please

224
00:13:25.008 --> 00:13:28.988
bear with me, we've got three, so anybody who's got samples, we'd like to increase

225
00:13:29.028 --> 00:13:32.648
this number, but when we look at the skin samples of patients with

226
00:13:32.708 --> 00:13:36.488
CIPN, we actually see significant increases in overall

227
00:13:36.588 --> 00:13:40.248
mRNA in those patients relative to age-matched unaffected

228
00:13:40.328 --> 00:13:44.128
